To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I respectfully request access to presidential and vice-presidential historical records maintained by the George W. Bush Presidential Library concerning the August 6, 2007 missile incident near Tsitelubani, Georgia.

For context on this event: 
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2007_Georgia_missile_incident

This request seeks records authored by, transmitted to, received by, circulated within, or maintained by the National Security Council (NSC) and the Office of the Vice President (OVP), including records maintained within NSC Europe/Eurasia directorate files, Executive Secretariat files, Situation Room reporting channels, and OVP national security staff files.

I. Scope of Request

I request access to all responsive electronic and textual records created, transmitted, circulated, or maintained between August 6th, 2007 and August 15th, 2007, including but not limited to:

diplomatic cables;
front-channel and back-channel communications;
SIPDIS or State Department traffic;
NSC-distributed cable reporting;
emails;
memoranda;
memoranda of conversation (memcons);
intelligence summaries;
briefing papers;
talking points;
situation reports;
interagency communications;
and attachments to responsive records.

This request specifically includes records relating to the missile strike, airspace violation, radar incident, missile recovery effort, forensic assessment, attribution assessment, or related diplomatic reporting associated with the August 2007 incident in Georgia.

II. Specific Categories of Requested Records

Diplomatic Reporting and Embassy Communications

All cables, memoranda, reporting traffic, or diplomatic correspondence sent by, sent to, received by, or referencing Ambassador John F. Tefft or the U.S. Embassy in Tbilisi between August 6, 2007 and August 15, 2007 concerning:

the Tsitelubani missile incident;
missile fragment recovery;
radar targeting allegations;
Russian military aircraft activity;
Georgian airspace violations;
anti-radiation missile assessments;
or related attribution and forensic analysis.

This request includes records designated or distributed as NODIS, EXDIS, SIPDIS, SECRET, or otherwise specially distributed State Department reporting.

Keyword and Subject-Matter Searches

I request searches for records containing one or more of the following terms, including reasonable spelling variations and transliterations:

“Tsitelubani”
“Tsithelubani”
“Tsitelubani incident”
"წითელუბანი"
“Kh-58”
“Raduga”
“anti-radiation missile”
“radar bombing”
“missile fragment”
“Joint Monitoring Group”
“International Group of Experts”
“IGE”
“Gori”
“Shavshvebi”
“airspace violation”
“forensic assessment”
“attribution assessment”
Internal NSC and OVP Assessments

All internal NSC or OVP emails, memoranda, briefing materials, or analytical assessments discussing:

Ambassador Tefft’s reporting;
intelligence or telemetry assessments;
missile fragment analysis;
interagency attribution discussions;
diplomatic response options;
public messaging guidance;
or communications strategy related to the incident.

III. Attachments and Embedded Materials

This request includes attachments to otherwise responsive communications, including but not limited to:

photographs;
satellite imagery;
drone-generated video;
missile-fragment imagery;
maps;
technical diagrams;
telemetry graphics;
forensic reports;
and briefing slides.

IV. Declassification Review and Segregability

To the extent that responsive records remain classified pursuant to Executive Order 13526 or related authorities, I request review for declassification and release of all reasonably segregable non-exempt portions.

Given the substantial passage of time since the events in question, I respectfully request that the Library consider discretionary release where appropriate and provide redacted copies rather than withholding records in full whenever possible.

For any records withheld in full, I request release of all reasonably segregable metadata, including:

document titles;
dates;
authors;
recipients;
subject lines;
archival control numbers;
and withdrawal sheets or equivalent tracking documentation.

If certain parts of this request or certain portions must be redacted please provide any reasonable segregable portion of a requested record after removing or redacting those portions claimed to be exempt, explain in writing the justification for redacting the record, indicate the extent of any redactions on the portion of the record which is made available or published and where technically feasible indicate on the redacted portion itself the specific exemption(s) claimed. 

The 2007 Tsitelubani incident is of real and legitimate historical value. Understanding the Kremlin's current fascism requires an examination of their behavior in Georgia. Thank you for the Bush library's commitment to transparency, and I look forward to working together on this request.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Robert Delaware
